description:
## Overarching Goal
Reduce decision paralysis in the bead approval flow by collapsing 7+ options into 2-3 simple choices, with advanced options available in a sub-menu for power users. This is progressive disclosure: simple by default, powerful on demand.

## Background & Reasoning
After creating beads, the approval flow (src/tools/approve.ts) presents options based on polish round:

**Round 0 (current — up to 7 options):**
1. ▶️ Start implementing
2. 🔍 Polish again (round 1)
3. 🧠 Fresh-agent refinement (round 1)
4. 🔨 Blunder hunt (5x overshoot)
5. 🔗 Dedup check
6. 🩺 Fix graph issues (conditional)
7. ❌ Reject

**Round 1+ (current — up to 8 options):**
1. ▶️ Start implementing
2. 🧠 Fresh-agent refinement (round N)
3. 🔍 Same-agent polish (may anchor) (round N)
4. 🔨 Blunder hunt (5x overshoot)
5. 🔗 Dedup check
6. 🔀 Cross-model review
7. 🩺 Fix graph issues (conditional)
8. ❌ Reject

Most users dont know the difference between these options. The system already knows the best action via convergence scoring.

## What to Change

### Simplified option structure:

**Round 0:**
1. ▶️ Start implementing
2. 🔍 Polish beads (round 1)
3. ⚙️ Advanced options...
4. ❌ Reject

**Round 1+:**
1. ▶️ Start implementing (with convergence info if available)
2. 🔍 Refine further (round N) — uses fresh-agent refinement (better after round 1)
3. ⚙️ Advanced options...
4. ❌ Reject

**Advanced sub-menu (presented via ctx.ui.select when "⚙️ Advanced" is chosen):**
- 🧠 Fresh-agent refinement — new context, no anchoring bias
- 🔍 Same-agent polish — faster, but may anchor on own output
- 🔨 Blunder hunt (5x overshoot) — exhaustive error search
- 🔗 Dedup check — find and merge duplicate beads
- 🔀 Cross-model review — alternative model second opinion (only shown round 1+)
- 🩺 Fix graph issues (N warnings) — only shown when graph issues exist
- ⬅️ Back to main menu

### Implementation details in src/tools/approve.ts:

#### Options construction (~line 296-330):
Replace the current `if (maxReached) / else if (round >= 1) / else` block with:

```typescript
const options: string[] = [];
if (maxReached) {
  options.push(startLabel, "❌ Reject");
} else {
  options.push(startLabel);
  if (round >= 1) {
    options.push(`🔍 Refine further (round ${round + 1})`);
  } else {
    options.push(`🔍 Polish beads (round ${round + 1})`);
  }
  options.push("⚙️ Advanced options...");
  options.push("❌ Reject");
}
```

#### Advanced sub-menu handler:
Add a new handler block for `choice?.startsWith("⚙️")`:

```typescript
if (choice?.startsWith("⚙️")) {
  const advancedOptions: string[] = [
    `🧠 Fresh-agent refinement (round ${round + 1})`,
    `🔍 Same-agent polish (round ${round + 1})`,
    `🔨 Blunder hunt (5x overshoot)`,
    `🔗 Dedup check`,
  ];
  if (round >= 1) {
    advancedOptions.push("🔀 Cross-model review");
  }
  if (hasGraphIssues) {
    advancedOptions.push(`🩺 Fix graph issues (${graphIssueCount} warning${graphIssueCount !== 1 ? "s" : ""})`);
  }
  advancedOptions.push("⬅️ Back");

  const advChoice = await ctx.ui.select(
    "⚙️ Advanced refinement options:",
    advancedOptions
  );

  if (!advChoice || advChoice.startsWith("⬅️")) {
    // Return to main approval menu
    return { content: [{ type: "text", text: "Call `orch_approve_beads` again to return to the approval menu." }], details: { approved: false } };
  }
  // Delegate to existing handlers by reassigning choice
  choice = advChoice;
  // Fall through to existing handler blocks below...
}
```

**KEY**: The delegation works by reassigning `choice` to the advanced sub-selection, then falling through to the existing `if (choice?.startsWith("🔍"))` / `if (choice?.startsWith("🧠"))` / etc. handler blocks. This means NO existing handler code changes — only the options array construction and the new "⚙️" handler are new code.

#### "🔍 Refine further" on round 1+ handler:
The top-level "🔍 Refine further" on round 1+ should delegate to the fresh-agent refinement path. This means the handler for `choice?.startsWith("🔍")` needs to check the round:

```typescript
if (choice?.startsWith("🔍")) {
  if (round >= 1 && !choice.includes("Same-agent")) {
    // "Refine further" on round 1+ → fresh-agent (better than same-agent after round 1)
    // Reuse the fresh-agent handler
    choice = `🧠 Fresh-agent refinement (round ${round + 1})`;
    // Fall through to 🧠 handler below
  } else {
    // Round 0 "Polish beads" or explicit "Same-agent polish" from Advanced menu
    // ... existing same-agent polish code ...
  }
}
```

Wait — this gets messy. Simpler approach: just restructure so "🔍 Refine further" is handled as a separate case that directly contains the fresh-agent refinement code (copied from the 🧠 handler). Or better: extract the fresh-agent and same-agent logic into helper functions called from both places.

Actually, the cleanest approach: after the Advanced sub-menu sets `choice` to the sub-selection, simply let the existing handler chain process it. The top-level "🔍 Refine further" on round 1+ gets its OWN handler that calls the fresh-agent code directly (duplicating the small amount of code from the 🧠 handler). This avoids fragile choice-reassignment tricks.

#### Preserving the convergence tip:
The convergenceTip (`"💡 Tip: Fresh-agent refinement recommended"`) should still appear in the select prompt text when convergence < 0.5 and round >= 1. It just becomes less critical since "Refine further" already defaults to fresh-agent.

### What is NOT changing (features preserved)
- ALL refinement modes still accessible via Advanced sub-menu
- Auto-approve on convergence unchanged
- Convergence scoring and display unchanged
- Quality gate before implementing unchanged
- Cross-model review full sub-flow unchanged
- Graph remediation full sub-flow unchanged
- Max polish rounds (12) unchanged
- Convergence tip still shown when relevant
- Polish change tracking and diff summaries unchanged

## Tests — src/tools/approve.test.ts

Add to the existing test file:

1. **Test: round 0 options** — Verify options array for round 0 contains exactly: Start, Polish, Advanced, Reject (in that order).

2. **Test: round 1+ options** — Verify options array for round 1+ contains exactly: Start, Refine further, Advanced, Reject.

3. **Test: maxReached options** — Verify max-rounds state only shows Start + Reject (no Advanced).

4. **Test: Advanced sub-menu includes all specialist options** — Verify the Advanced options list contains fresh-agent, same-agent, blunder, dedup. Verify cross-model only appears on round 1+. Verify graph fix only appears when hasGraphIssues is true.

5. **Test: "Refine further" round 1+ delegates to fresh-agent** — Verify that selecting "🔍 Refine further" on round 1+ produces the same result as selecting fresh-agent refinement (returns freshAgent=true in details).

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Round 0 shows exactly 4 options: Start, Polish, Advanced, Reject
- [ ] Round 1+ shows exactly 4 options: Start, Refine further, Advanced, Reject
- [ ] maxReached shows only Start + Reject (unchanged)
- [ ] "Refine further" on round 1+ uses fresh-agent refinement
- [ ] Advanced sub-menu contains all specialist options
- [ ] Cross-model review only in Advanced after round 1
- [ ] Graph fix only in Advanced when issues exist
- [ ] "Back" from Advanced returns to main approval menu
- [ ] All existing handlers unchanged — only access path restructured
- [ ] Auto-approve on convergence still works
- [ ] Convergence tip still shown when relevant
- [ ] Tests verify option structure for round 0, round 1+, maxReached, and Advanced contents
- [ ] npm run build passes
- [ ] npm test passes

### Files: src/tools/approve.ts, src/tools/approve.test.ts

Create a shared context object that extracted modules can use instead of closing over module-level variables.

## Problem
index.ts has ~15 module-level variables (state, orchestratorActive, worktreePool, sophiaCRResult, etc.) that all tool/command handlers close over. When we extract handlers into separate files, they need access to these.

## Solution
Define an OrchestratorContext interface in src/types.ts:

```typescript
export interface OrchestratorContext {
  state: OrchestratorState;
  pi: ExtensionAPI;
  orchestratorActive: boolean;
  worktreePool?: WorktreePool;
  sophiaCRResult?: PlanToCRResult;
  swarmTender?: SwarmTender;
  setPhase: (phase: OrchestratorPhase, ctx: ExtensionContext) => void;
  persistState: () => void;
  updateWidget: (ctx: ExtensionContext) => void;
  runHitMeAgents: (configs: {name:string,task:string}[], cwd: string, ctx: ExtensionContext) => Promise<HitMeResult>;
  agentMailRPC: (tool: string, args: Record<string,unknown>) => Promise<any>;
  ensureAgentMailProject: (cwd: string) => Promise<void>;
}
```

Create this interface and export it. Do NOT refactor index.ts yet — just define the contract.
Also export HitMeResult interface.

## Acceptance criteria
- [ ] OrchestratorContext interface defined in src/types.ts
- [ ] HitMeResult interface exported
- [ ] npm run build passes
- [ ] npm test passes

